<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
  <meta charset="UTF-8">
  <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0">
  <title>Finding 5 · Reflected XSS</title>
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/style.css">
  <link rel="stylesheet" href="/css/learn.css">
</head>
<body>
  <div class="learn-page">
    <div class="brand brand-sm" style="margin-bottom: 24px;">
      <span class="brand-mark">⛨</span>
      <span>CySER Workshop · Skyway engagement</span>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-hero">
      <div class="hero-icon">🧪</div>
      <h1>Finding 5 confirmed</h1>
      <p class="hero-subtitle">Day 5 · Reflected XSS + Cookie Exfiltration</p>
      <div class="flag-badge"><%= flag %></div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-grid">
      <div class="learn-card skill-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📚</div>
        <h2>The vulnerability</h2>
        <h3>HTML injection from user input</h3>
        <p>The server pasted your search query into the page without escaping <code>&lt;</code>, <code>&gt;</code>, or <code>"</code>. Your <code>&lt;script&gt;</code> tag became real JavaScript with full access to the page's DOM, cookies, and any same-origin endpoint.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card world-card">
        <div class="card-icon">📰</div>
        <h2>Seen in the wild</h2>
        <h3>British Airways · 2018</h3>
        <p>An XSS-led skimmer on British Airways' payment page leaked the card details of 380,000 customers. ICO fined them £20M. XSS isn't a popup-alert prank. It's the entry point for session theft, drive-by malware, and supply-chain attacks. Most major sites still have reflected XSS lurking in some corner.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card career-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🛠️</div>
        <h2>How to fix it</h2>
        <h3>Context-aware escaping + CSP</h3>
        <p>Use templating that escapes by default (<code>&lt;%= %&gt;</code> in EJS, <code>{{ }}</code> in most frameworks). Mark sensitive cookies <code>HttpOnly</code> so JS can't read them. Add a strict Content-Security-Policy that disallows inline scripts. Defense in depth. Any one of these alone catches the rest.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="learn-card key-card">
        <div class="card-icon">🔑</div>
        <h2>One-line takeaway</h2>
        <h3>Output encoding, not input filtering</h3>
        <p>Don't try to "sanitize" input on the way in (you'll miss something). Encode on the way out, with awareness of where the data lands. HTML body, attribute, JS string, URL. Each context needs its own escape rules.</p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="learn-nav">
      <a href="/" class="nav-btn secondary">← All findings</a>
      <% if (hasNext) { %><a href="/challenge/<%= nextNum %>" class="nav-btn primary">Day <%= nextNum %> →</a><% } %>
    </div>
  </div>
</body>
</html>
